rded by Statistics Canada are not the result of Pentecostals abandoning their congregations; rather, they are indicative of a radical transformation from traditionally Pentecostal to generically evangelical modes of religious identity, belief, and practice that are changing the ways that Pentecostals understand and explain their religious identities. The case study presented in this book suggests that a new breed of Canadian Pentecostals are emerging for whom traditional definitions and expressions of Pentecostalism are much less important than religious autonomy and individualism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPentecostal churchesxCanada. 0aPentecostal churchesxOntarioxWaterloo (Regional municipality). 0aPentecostal churcheszCanada. 0aPentecostal churcheszOntariozWaterloo (Regional municipality). 0aPentecostal churches. 0aPentecostalismxCanadaxOntarioxWaterloo (Regional municipality). 0aPentecostalismxCanada. 0aPentecostalismxOntarioxWaterloo (Regional municipality). 0aPentecostalismzCanada. 0aPentecostalismzOntariozWaterloo (Regional municipality). 4aReligion. 4aSocial Science: Sociology. 4aWaterloo Region. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Pentecostal & Charismatic.2bisacsh  aCanadian Pentecostalism.  abaptism of the Holy Spirit.  acongregational studies.  adivine healing.  aethnography.  aexorcism.  ageneric evangelicalism.  amiracles.  areligion in Canada.  areligious change.  areligious identity.  asociology of religion.  aspeaking in tongues.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z978311127703540uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112141540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771121415423Coveruhttps://www.degru